2. CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)

One of the most important web attacks.


---

Imagine

You are logged into Barclays.

Browser stores:

Session Cookie

SESSION=abc123

Now you visit a malicious website.

Hidden inside:

<form action="https://barclays.com/transfer">

<input name="amount" value="100000">

<input name="to" value="attacker">

</form>

<script>
document.forms[0].submit();
</script>

Browser automatically sends:

Cookie:
SESSION=abc123

Server thinks:

> Legitimate Barclays user.



Money transferred.

You never clicked anything.


---

Attack Flow

User logs into bank

↓

Browser stores session cookie

↓

User opens evil website

↓

Hidden request created

↓

Browser automatically sends cookie

↓

Bank trusts cookie

↓

Attack succeeds


---

Why is CSRF possible?

Because browsers automatically attach cookies.

The attacker doesn't need to know your password.

They only trick your browser.


---

Real Example

Logged into:

gmail.com

Visit:

evil.com

evil.com sends

POST

/changePassword

Browser includes Gmail cookie.

Google thinks:

Real user requested it.


---

3. Anti-CSRF Tokens

Industry standard defense.


---

Idea

Every sensitive form gets a secret random value.

Example

Token

92h7sd72d8a

Server stores it.

Form contains

<input hidden>

csrf=92h7sd72d8a

When request arrives:

Server checks

Cookie

+

CSRF Token

Both must match.


---

Why attacker cannot send token?

Because:

Same-Origin Policy prevents attacker from reading the legitimate webpage.

The attacker can make the browser send the cookie, but cannot read the secret token embedded in the genuine page.


Without token

↓

Rejected


---

Flow

User opens bank

↓

Server generates token

↓

Browser receives token

↓

User submits form

↓

Cookie + Token

↓

Server validates

↓

Success

Attacker:

Cookie

×

No Token

↓

Rejected


---

Manager's WHY

Why are Anti-CSRF Tokens preferred?

Because cookies are automatically sent.

Tokens are not automatically sent.

Attacker cannot guess them.

They prove the request originated from the legitimate application.


---

4. SameSite Cookies

Modern browsers provide another defense.

Cookie example

Set-Cookie

SESSION=abc

SameSite=Strict


---

SameSite=Strict

Cookie sent only from same website.

Example

barclays.com

↓

barclays.com

✔ Cookie sent

evil.com

↓

barclays.com

❌ Cookie blocked


---

SameSite=Lax

Allows cookies for normal top-level navigation (such as clicking a link), but blocks them for most cross-site background requests like hidden forms or iframes.

Much safer than having no SameSite protection.


---

SameSite=None

Cookie always sent.

Needs Secure.

Highest CSRF risk.


---

Manager's WHY

Why does SameSite=Lax reduce risk?

Because most CSRF attacks rely on the browser automatically sending cookies with cross-site POSTs or embedded requests. SameSite=Lax blocks cookies in most of those cases, so many CSRF attacks fail.

It doesn't eliminate all CSRF scenarios, so sensitive actions should still use anti-CSRF tokens.


---

5. Origin & Referer Validation

Server can inspect request headers.

Example

Origin

https://barclays.com

or

Referer

https://barclays.com/profile

If request comes from

evil.com

↓

Reject.


---

Why use this?

Additional security layer.

Not perfect because some clients or privacy settings may omit these headers.


---

Manager's WHY

Why doesn't HTTPS stop CSRF?

HTTPS encrypts traffic between the browser and the server.

It does not stop a user's browser from sending a legitimate authenticated request to the server. If the browser is tricked into making the request, HTTPS protects that malicious request in transit too.

CSRF is an authorization/request-origin problem, not an encryption problem.


---

Quick Interview Revision

Authentication

Who are you?

Authorization

What are you allowed to do?

CSRF

Forces a logged-in user's browser to send unwanted requests.

Why CSRF works

Browsers automatically attach session cookies.

Anti-CSRF Token

A random secret included in the request that attackers cannot obtain, allowing the server to verify the request came from the legitimate application.

SameSite Cookie

Restricts when browsers send cookies on cross-site requests, reducing CSRF risk.

Origin/Referer Validation

Checks whether the request originated from a trusted website.


---

30-Second Manager Answer

> "Authentication verifies a user's identity, while authorization determines what that user is allowed to access. CSRF exploits the browser's automatic inclusion of session cookies to perform actions on behalf of a logged-in user. HTTPS encrypts the request but doesn't prevent CSRF because the browser still sends authenticated requests. We mitigate CSRF using anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and Origin/Referer validation. Anti-CSRF tokens are preferred because only the legitimate application can provide the correct token, proving the request originated from a trusted page."
